SIMPLE: shrink
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Shrink
<hw>Shrink</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.</pos>
<conjf>Shrank</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr> or <conjf>Shrunk</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>
<pos>p. p.</pos> <conjf>Shrunk</conjf> or <conjf>Shrunken</conjf>
<pr>(<?/)</pr>, but the latter is now seldom used except as a
participial adjective; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Shrinking</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>shrinken</ets>,
<ets>schrinken</ets>, AS. <ets>scrincan</ets>; akin to OD.
<ets>schrincken</ets>, and probably to Sw. <ets>skrynka</ets> a wrinkle,
<ets>skrynkla</ets> to wrinkle, to rumple, and E. <ets>shrimp</ets>, n.
& v., <ets>scrimp</ets>. CF. <er>Shrimp</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
wrinkle, bend, or curl; to shrivel; hence, to contract into a less
extent or compass; to gather together; to become compacted.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And on a broken reed he still did stay⟦br⟧
His feeble steps, which <qex>shrunk</qex> when hard thereon he lay.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I have not found that water, by mixture of ashes, will
<qex>shrink</qex> or draw into less room.</q>
<rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Against this fire do I <qex>shrink</qex> up.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And <qex>shrink</qex> like parchment in consuming fire.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>All the boards did <qex>shrink</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Coleridge.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To withdraw or retire, as from danger; to decline
action from fear; to recoil, as in fear, horror, or distress.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>What happier natures <qex>shrink</qex> at with affright,⟦br⟧
The hard inhabitant contends is right.</q> <rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They assisted us against the Thebans when you <qex>shrank</qex>
from the task.</q> <rj><qau>Jowett (Thucyd.)</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To express fear, horror, or pain by contracting the
body, or part of it; to shudder; to quake.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Shrink</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Shrink
<hw>Shrink</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To cause to contract
or shrink; <as>as, to <ex>shrink</ex> finnel by immersing it in boiling
water</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To draw back; to withdraw.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The Libyc Hammon <qex>shrinks</qex> his horn.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To shrink on</b></col> <fld>(Mach.)</fld>, <cd>to fix
(one piece or part) firmly around (another) by natural contraction in
cooling, as a tire on a wheel, or a hoop upon a cannon, which is made
slightly smaller than the part it is to fit, and expanded by heat till
it can be slipped into place.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Shrink</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Shrink
<hw>Shrink</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act shrinking;
shrinkage; contraction; also, recoil; withdrawal.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Yet almost wish, with sudden <qex>shrink</qex>,⟦br⟧
That I had less to praise.</q> <rj><qau>Leigh Hunt.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <ety>[Contraction of head-<ets>shrink</ets>er, a
colloquial term for psychiatrist.]</ety> <def>a psychiatrist.</def>
<mark>[Coll.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Shrinkage</ent>⟦br⟧
